I think you’ve landed on something that’s broader than marketing. It’s a category innovation pipeline.

Most innovation isn’t inventing from nothing. It’s taking an existing category, finding where it conflates different needs or assumptions, separating those pieces, and then designing around one of the newly exposed “cracks.”

A generalized pipeline could look like:

Observe Existing Category
        ↓
Mirror
(Why does this category exist?)
        ↓
Hammer
(What different jobs or meanings are compressed together?)
        ↓
Crack Discovery
(Where are customers making tradeoffs?)
        ↓
Flank
(Choose one overlooked dimension to optimize.)
        ↓
Kintsugi
(Reassemble into a new category with a clear identity.)
        ↓
ZPC
(Compress into one memorable phrase or mental model.)

